problem_text:
If Problem 17.64 has an affirmative answer, does it follow that, for some function g(p), the number of isomorphism classes of g(p)-approximations to J is
a) countable?
b) one?
Note that if, for some g(p), there are only finitely many isomorphism classes, then for some h(p) there is only one.
C. R. Leedham-Green
